SEBASTIAN STRANGE, Eco-Architect, environmental issues

I think the issue of climate change is still too little recognized as a global urgency. Nine out of ten times the reason why people do claim to have a problem, is because it is seen as something distant and ‘not something to worry too much about’. Yet all the burning glaciers, hot summers, collapsing shallows, dying marine ecosystems and mass-extinctions are a result of the collective carbon footprint of our economic system and our individual lifestyles.

The very definition of development tends to be based on destruction and exploitation of nature’s resources. We need to recognize that we are part of nature. To step back and understand what our role in this world, and what our responsibility is, as humans on earth. This awareness is a good start to design a globally fair and balanced, decentralized social and economic system that serves nature and each other.

LEA JAKLICH & INGRID NOTTEN, Parketuhr Munich (Urban M
